However, there is a limit to what data and statistics can do.  Sometimes it is not possible to determine two different effects from the data. What is needed is a picture of reality to link the data with the question. Reality has a face and a language that can be described. This is the language of graphs (or equations). It is important to listen to the causal story and be able to formalise that mathematically. 

For example, Simpson's paradox: treatment seems to be helpful to men, helpful to women but appears to have adverse effects on the population. It is important now to tell a story.  Why could this happen?  Are women more likely to seek help?  Are they more likely to recover? What is the selection process?  Can this be drawn on a graph.  All that is required is a couple of errors. 

Once the graph (equation) is completed, it is added to the data to get an answer to the question of whether the drug is effective or not. The data are numbers in a context?  Data can speak many voices until they are managed.  The context of the data (way that it was collected) can be added to the story or equation.  If education is a confounder, this can be tested. 

It is important to make the assumptions clear and transparent so that they can be discussed and, if necessary, replaced. 
